<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="24" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="25.[192,1441,291,1915]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[240,395,1667,1691]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name means “chestnut-brown” referring to the deep red-brown dorsal color on this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="24" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="25.[192,1441,291,1915]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[240,630,1731,1755]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">Distribution and phenology.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Austin and Mielke" authorityYear="2008" box="[635,902,1731,1755]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Porphyrogenes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spadix">
<emphasis box="[635,902,1731,1755]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">Porphyrogenes spadix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[1192,1258,1732,1756]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">types</typeStatus>
taken in June, August, October, and November.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="24" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="25.[192,1441,291,1915]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[240,592,1795,1819]" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">Diagnosis and discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Austin and Mielke" authorityYear="2008" box="[598,864,1795,1819]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Porphyrogenes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spadix">
<emphasis box="[598,864,1795,1819]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">Porphyrogenes spadix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is immediately identified by its deep red-brown color in comparison with the more tawny dorsa of most 
<taxonomicName box="[855,1034,1827,1851]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Porphyrogenes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[855,1034,1827,1851]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">Porphyrogenes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The configuration of the harpe is reminiscent of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Austin and Mielke" authorityYear="2008" box="[373,513,1860,1883]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Porphyrogenes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="convexus">
<emphasis box="[373,513,1860,1883]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="24">P. convexus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with its broadened caudal end, but other structures of the genitalia are very different.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
